TanStack Start provides built-in type safety for search parameters out of the box, treating them as validated route state. In contrast, Next.js offers generic string-based search params via `URLSearchParams`, while Nuxt validates routes but doesn't automatically type `route.query` values. With TanStack Router, you define a schema for search params (e.g., `{ user: string }`) using `validateSearch`, and the framework ensures type correctness throughout the component. For example:
tsx
export const Route = createFileRoute('/')({
  validateSearch: (search): { user: string } => ({
    user: typeof search.user === 'string' ? search.user : '',
  }),
});

This results in `Route.useSearch()` returning a fully typed object, enabling shareable URLs and eliminating manual client-side state management.

Yes. TanStack Start’s `createServerFn` handles both reads and writes with the same API. Here’s an example of a server function for reading GitHub user data:
tsx
import { createServerFn } from '@tanstack/react-start';

interface GithubUser {
  login: string;
  name: string | null;
  // ... other fields
}

const getGithubUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' })
  .inputValidator((username: string) => username)
  .handler(async ({ data: username }): Promise<GithubUser> => {
    const res = await fetch(`https://api.github.com/users/${username}`, {
      headers: { Accept: 'application/vnd.github+json' },
    });
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`User "${username}" not found`);
    return (await res.json()) as GithubUser;
  });

To perform a mutation (e.g., POST), you’d reuse the same function but call it with `method: 'POST'` and include a body parameter. The function is called directly from a route loader or component without additional boilerplate, and the type (`GithubUser`) propagates automatically.

TanStack Start enforces type safety end-to-end by default, connecting types for route params, search params, and loader data in a single chain. For example, when you define a route with `createFileRoute`, the `validateSearch` function types the search params, and the `loader` uses those params to fetch data. The types flow from the route definition to the component without manual annotation:
tsx
export const Route = createFileRoute('/')({
  validateSearch: (search): { user: string } => ({ user: search.user || '' }),
  loader: async ({ deps: { user } }) => {
    return { user: await getGithubUser({ data: user }) };
  },
});

This ensures that route navigation, search params, and data fetching are all type-checked, reducing runtime errors and boilerplate.

Here’s a step-by-step implementation for a GitHub user lookup app:

1. **Define the server function** (e.g., `getGithubUser`) as shown in the previous example.
2. **Set up the route** with typed search params and a loader:
tsx
export const Route = createFileRoute('/')({
  validateSearch: (search): { user: string } => ({
    user: typeof search.user === 'string' ? search.user : '',
  }),
  loaderDeps: ({ search: { user } }) => ({ user }),
  loader: async ({ deps: { user } }) => {
    if (!user) return { user: null, error: null };
    try {
      const userData = await getGithubUser({ data: user });
      return { user: userData, error: null };
    } catch (error) {
      return { user: null, error: error.message };
    }
  },
  component: Home,
});

3. **Create the component** to display the user data:
tsx
function Home() {
  const { user, error } = Route.useLoaderData();
  const [input, setInput] = React.useState('');

  return (
    <div>
      <form onSubmit={(e) => {
        e.preventDefault();
        navigate({ search: { user: input.trim() } });
      }}>
        <input value={input} onChange={(e) => setInput(e.target.value)} />
        <button type="submit">Lookup</button>
      </form>
      {user && (
        <div>
          <img src={user.avatar_url} alt={user.login} />
          <h1>{user.name}</h1>
          <p>{user.bio}</p>
        </div>
      )}
      {error && <p>Error: {error}</p>}
    </div>
  );
}

This app fetches data server-side, validates search params, and handles errors, all with full type safety.
